| Granny Sues RIAA Over Unlicensed Investigator                      |
|   from the more-ways-to-hit-them-back dept.                        |
|   posted by kdawson on Tuesday July 03, @20:43 (The Courts)        |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/07/03/2323203          |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]NewYorkCountryLawyer writes "An elderly, non-file-sharing grandmother
from East Texas, who had been [1]sued by the RIAA after being displaced
by Hurricane Rita, has [2]sought leave to file counterclaims against the
RIAA record companies for [3]using unlicensed investigators. In her
[4]counterclaims (PDF) Ms. Crain claims that the record companies
'entered into an agreement with a private investigations company to
provide investigative services which led to the production of evidence to
be used in court against counterclaim plaintiff, including the
identification of an IP address on the basis of which counterclaim
defendants filed their suit... [They] were at the time of this agreement
aware that the aforementioned private investigations company was
unlicensed to conduct investigations in the State of Texas specifically,
and in other states as well... [T]hey agreed between themselves and
understood that unlicensed and unlawful investigations would take place
in order to provide evidence for this lawsuit, as well as thousands of
others as part of a mass litigation campaign... [T]he private
investigations company hired by plaintiffs engaged in one or more overt
acts of unlawful private investigation... Such actions constitute civil
conspiracy under Texas common law.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/07/03/2323203

Links:
    0. http://recordingindustryvspeople.blogspot.com/
    1. http://p2pnet.net/story/10575
    2. http://recordingindustryvspeople.blogspot.com/2007/07/ms-crain-counterclaims-against-riaa-for.html
    3. http://www.p2pnet.net/story/12674
    4. http://www.ilrweb.com/viewILRPDF.asp?filename=sony_crain_070703MotAmendAnsCounterclaims


