+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Perpetual Energy Machine Getting Lots of Attention                 |
|   from the swimming-in-snake-oil dept.                             |
|   posted by ScuttleMonkey on Wednesday July 04, @14:46 (Science)   |
|   http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/07/04/1628259      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

Many users have written to tell us about a magnetic machine promising "[0]infinite
clean energy". Engadget has the first picture of the device and is
reporting that the announcement (along with a short video) of this
supposed device will be released later tonight. "CEO Sean McCarthy tells
SilconRepublic how it works. Namely, the time variance in magnetic fields
allows the Orbo platform to 'consistently produce power, going against
the law of conservation of energy which states that energy cannot be
created or destroyed.' He goes on to say 'It's too good to be true but it
is true. It will have such an impact on everything we do. The only
analogy I can give is if you had absolute proof that God wasn't real.'"
In my experience if something seems too good to be true it generally is.
I wouldn't get your hopes up.

Discuss this story at:
    http://science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/07/04/1628259

Links:
    0. http://www.engadget.com/2007/07/04/steorns-orbo-free-energy-machine-demonstrated-tomorrow/


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Minisode Network Condenses TV Shows to Under Six Minutes           |
|   from the readers-digest-television dept.                         |
|   posted by ScuttleMonkey on Wednesday July 04, @15:38 (The Interne|
|   http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/07/04/1657245              |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

CNN is reporting on a (relatively) new website called [0]the Minisode
Network that allows users to watch popular television shows that have
been strategically condensed down to somewhere between four and six
minutes. "Don't think of the Minisode Network as a brand-new Web site.
Think of it as a long-overdue public service. That is, who among us
hasn't felt the double-edged sword of our media age: So much video from
TV, DVDs, the Internet and even cell phones ... but too little time to
watch it all? The Minisode Network has a solution. Launched in June as a
broadband channel on the MySpace site, it offers, for our streaming
pleasure, episodes of vintage Sony Pictures Television series like
'Silver Spoons,' 'Starsky & Hutch,' 'Diff'rent Strokes' and even Ricki
Lake's talk show."

Discuss this story at:
    http://slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/07/04/1657245

Links:
    0. http://www.cnn.com/2007/TECH/ptech/07/03/la.minisodes.ap/index.html


